snippet.textDisplay: when i got my first apartment... every dinner was a pasta side and a can of vegetables. thats a full meal, with some protein and some vegetables. was it great? no, but it was nutrition. and it was CHEAP. $1 for the pasta side, 50 cents for the vegetables, plus a few bucks for milk for the week. given the low cost and the low prep time, that's a really hard standard to beat to convince people to cook more. when i DID get into cooking fresh foods, i had two reasons- first of all because i just DIDNT want to eat like that anymore, i was sick of it after a few years, but also because i moved in with someone. cooking for one person is *hard*, and its hard to want to put the effort in when you can settle for less. it's hard to justify the amount of money and time and effort it takes to cook fresh food for one portion, or to make meal prep when youre going to eat it all yourself and end up sick of it. i would say thats one of the biggest motivational barriers to putting the effort into cooking and buying fresh foods.
